{ The kings were on d5 and c8 here; but we shall not place them on the board just yet - let's deal with the squares of correspondence first.
Two pairs of squares of reciprocal zugzwang are obvious right off, d6/d8 and c5/c7. The squares d6 and c5 border on d5; and for black, the corresponding squares d8 and c7 border on c8. Thus, a standard means of identifying new correspondence: that of the d5- and c8-squares.
Along with d5 and c5, white has two equally important squares: c4 and d4. Black also has two corresponding squares, b8 and d8, but the are not connected, while c4 and d4 are.
